{META_DATA}: "SIDEWAYS"
{META_DATA}: Screenplay by
{META_DATA}: Alexander Payne & Jim Taylor
{META_DATA}: Based on the novel by
{META_DATA}: Rex Pickett
{META_DATA}: May 29, 2003
{META_DATA}: UNDER THE STUDIO LOGO:
{META_DATA}: KNOCKING at a door and distant dog BARKING.
{META_DATA}: NOW UNDER BLACK, a CARD --
{META_DATA}: SATURDAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The rapping, at first tentative and polite, grows insistent.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Then we hear someone get out of bed.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILES (O.S.)
{DIALOGUE}: ...the fuck...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A DOOR is opened, and the black gives way to BLINDING WHITE LIGHT, the way one experiences the first glimpse of day amid, say, a hangover.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A WORKER is there.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILES (O.S.)
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WORKER
{DIALOGUE}: Hi, Miles.
{DIALOGUE}: Can you move your car, please?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILES (O.S.)
{DIALOGUE}: Why?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WORKER
{DIALOGUE}: The painters got to put the truck in, and you didn't park too good.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILES (O.S.)
{META_DATA}: (a sigh, then --)
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, hold on.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He closes the door with a SLAM.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. MILES'S APARTMENT COMPLEX - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SUPERIMPOSE --
{META_DATA}: SAN DIEGO, CALIFORNIA
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Wearing only underwear, a bathrobe and clogs, MILES RAYMOND comes out of his unit and heads toward the street.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He passes some SIX MEXICANS waiting to work.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He climbs into his twelve-year-old CONVERTIBLE SAAB, parked far from the curb and blocking part of the driveway.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The car starts fitfully.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he pulls away, the guys begin backing up the truck.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. STREET - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Miles rounds the corner and finds a new parking spot.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. CAR - CONTINUOUS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He cuts the engine, exhales a long breath and brings his hands to his head in a gesture of headache pain or just anguish.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He leans back in his seat, closes his eyes, and soon NODS OFF.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. MILES'S APARTMENT - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The door bursts open.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Miles runs into the kitchen, looking just past camera.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILES
{DIALOGUE}: Fuck!
{META_DATA}: WHIP PAN TO --
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: THE MICROWAVE CLOCK that reads 10:50.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ON THE PHONE --
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Miles hurriedly throws clothes into a suitcase.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILES
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, no, I know I said I'd be there by noon, but there's been all this work going on at my building, and it's like a total nightmare, and I had a bunch of stuff to deal with this morning.
{DIALOGUE}: But I'm on my way.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm out the door right this second.
{DIALOGUE}: It's going to be great.
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah.
{DIALOGUE}: Bye.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. MILES'S BATHROOM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ON THE TOILET --
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Miles has a BOOK propped open on his knees.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He turns a page, lost in his reading.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: LATER --
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Miles SHOWERS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: IN THE MIRROR --
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Miles FLOSSES.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. COFFEE HOUSE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Miles finally makes it to the front of the line.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BARISTA
{DIALOGUE}: Hey, Miles.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILES
{DIALOGUE}: Hey, Simon.
{DIALOGUE}: Triple espresso, please.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BARISTA
{DIALOGUE}: Rough night, huh?
{META_DATA}: (ringing it up)
{DIALOGUE}: For here?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILES
{DIALOGUE}: No, I'm running late.
{DIALOGUE}: Make it to go.
{DIALOGUE}: And give me a New York Times and...
{META_DATA}: (scanning the display case)
{DIALOGUE}: ...a spinach croissant.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. 5 FREEWAY ENTRANCE RAMP - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Miles's Saab chugs up the ramp and merges.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: INSERT - NEW YORK TIMES CROSSWORD PUZZLE --
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: -- pressed against the STEERING WHEEL.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The puzzle is about 1/3 finished.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. 5 FREEWAY - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As though from an adjacent car, we see Miles driving while carefully filling in an answer.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT./EXT. SAAB - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: THROUGH THE WINDSHIELD --
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A SIGN reads:
{META_DATA}: RANCHO PALOS VERDES PALOS VERDES ESTATES 1/4 MILE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: PAN TO MILES as he signals to change lanes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The finished puzzle lies on the passenger seat.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. PALOS VERDES STREET - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The houses on this block are blandly palatial as in so many affluent Southern California suburbs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Miles's car pull into the driveway behind an older BMW and two LEXI.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He gets out and trots toward the front door.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. ERGANIAN HOUSE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A GIANT PROJECTION TV --
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In a large split-level living room displays a GOLF TOURNAMENT.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: WIDE --
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Watching from the ultra-comfortable furniture are MIKE ERGANIAN, a tanned, silver-haired real estate caudillo; bride- to-be CHRISTINE ERGANIAN, his oldest daughter; and JACK LOPATE, wearing bowling shirt, shorts and flip-flops.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MRS. ERGANIAN, a warm and elegant housewife, shows Miles into the room.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. ERGANIAN
{DIALOGUE}: Look what the cat dragged!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILES
{DIALOGUE}: Hi, everybody.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mr. Erganian and Jack get to their feet and shake hands with Miles.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jack remains affable, but we can discern his genuine irritation.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: About time you got here, bud.
{DIALOGUE}: Mr. Prompt.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MR. ERGANIAN
{DIALOGUE}: We were thinking maybe you took the wrong way and went to Tijuana and they didn't let you back in.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Erganians laugh.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Miles works up a smile too.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILES
{DIALOGUE}: I had to bribe them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: More lame laughter.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRISTINE
{DIALOGUE}: Hey, Miles.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILES
{META_DATA}: (leaning in to kiss Christine)
{DIALOGUE}: Seriously though, the freeway was unbelievable today.
{DIALOGUE}: Unbelievable.
{DIALOGUE}: Bumper to bumper the whole way.
{DIALOGUE}: People getting an early start on the weekend, I guess.
{DIALOGUE}: Granted I got a late start, but still.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Although Mr. Erganian presses MUTE on the remote, he keeps watching for an extended moment, as do Jack and Miles.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. ERGANIAN
{DIALOGUE}: Christine, why don't you ask Miles about the cake?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRISTINE
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, good idea.
{DIALOGUE}: Here, Miles, come to the kitchen with me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: Don't bother him with that.
{DIALOGUE}: We got to get going.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRISTINE
{META_DATA}: (taking Miles's hand)
{DIALOGUE}: It'll just take a second.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. ERGANIAN KITCHEN - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jack and the Erganians surround Miles as he eats from a plate with two pieces of CAKE -- one white, one dark.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. ERGANIAN
{DIALOGUE}: Jack tells us you are publishing a book.
{DIALOGUE}: Congratulations.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MR. ERGANIAN
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, congratulations.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Miles shoots Jack a look.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mr. Erganian gets some ice cubes from the refrigerator door.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILES
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, well, it's not exactly finalized yet, but, um, there has been some interest and --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MRS. ERGANIAN
{META_DATA}: (to Jack)
{DIALOGUE}: Your friend is modest.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, Miles, don't be so modest.
{DIALOGUE}: Indulge them.
{DIALOGUE}: Don't make me out to be a liar.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MR. ERGANIAN
{DIALOGUE}: What subject is your book?
{DIALOGUE}: Non- fiction?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILES
{DIALOGUE}: No, it's a novel.
{DIALOGUE}: Fiction.
{DIALOGUE}: Although there's a lot from my own life, so I guess technically some of it is non- fiction.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MR. ERGANIAN
{DIALOGUE}: Good, I like non-fiction.
{DIALOGUE}: There is so much to know about the world that I think reading a story someone just invented is kind of a waste of time.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRISTINE
{DIALOGUE}: So which one do you like better?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILES
{DIALOGUE}: I like them both, but if pressed I'd have to say I prefer the dark.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{META_DATA}: (to Christine)
{DIALOGUE}: See?
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. SAAB - CONTINUOUS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: IN A REAR VIEW MIRROR --
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Erganians wave good-bye.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: INSIDE THE CAR --
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Miles accelerates as he and Jack wave back.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: Where the fuck were you, man?
{DIALOGUE}: I was dying in there.
{DIALOGUE}: We were supposed to be a hundred miles away by now.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILES
{DIALOGUE}: I can't help the traffic.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: Come on.
{DIALOGUE}: You're fucking hungover.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILES
{DIALOGUE}: Okay, there was a tasting last night.
{DIALOGUE}: But I wanted to get us some stuff for the ride up.
{DIALOGUE}: Check out the box.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jack turns around, and starts rooting around in a CARDBOARD WINE BOX.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILES
{DIALOGUE}: Why did you tell them my book was being published?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: You said you had it all lined up.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILES
{DIALOGUE}: No, I didn't.
{DIALOGUE}: What I said was that my agent had heard there was some interest at Conundrum...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, Conundrum.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILES
{DIALOGUE}: ...and that one of the editors was passing it up to a senior editor.
{DIALOGUE}: She was supposed to hear something this week, but now it's next week, and... It's always like this.
{DIALOGUE}: It's always a fucking waiting game.
{DIALOGUE}: I've been through it too many times already.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: I don't know.
{DIALOGUE}: Senior editor?
{DIALOGUE}: Sounds like you're in to me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILES
{DIALOGUE}: It's a long shot, all right?
{DIALOGUE}: And Conundrum is just a small specialty press anyway.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm not getting my hopes up.
{DIALOGUE}: I've stopped caring.
{DIALOGUE}: That's it.
{DIALOGUE}: I've stopped caring.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jack sits back in his seat holding up a bottle of CHAMPAGNE and TWO GLASSES.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: But I know it's going to happen this time.
{DIALOGUE}: I can feel it.
{DIALOGUE}: This is the one.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm proud of you, man.
{DIALOGUE}: You're the smartest guy I know.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jack now begins to remove the foil from the champagne bottle.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILES
{DIALOGUE}: Don't open that now.
{DIALOGUE}: It's warm.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: Come on, we're celebrating.
{DIALOGUE}: I say we pop it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILES
{DIALOGUE}: That's a 1992 Byron.
{DIALOGUE}: It's really rare.
{DIALOGUE}: Don't open it now.
{DIALOGUE}: I've been saving it!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jack untwists the wire.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Instantly the cork pops off, and a fountain of champagne erupts.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILES
{DIALOGUE}: For Christ's Sake, Jack!
{DIALOGUE}: You just wasted like half of it!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jack begins pouring two glasses.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: Shut up.
{META_DATA}: (handing Miles a glass)
{DIALOGUE}: Here's to a great week.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILES
{META_DATA}: (coming around)
{DIALOGUE}: Yes.
{DIALOGUE}: Absolutely.
{DIALOGUE}: Despite your crass behavior, I'm really glad we're finally getting this time together.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILES
{DIALOGUE}: You know how long I've been begging to take you on the wine tour.
{DIALOGUE}: I was beginning to think it was never going to happen.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They clink and drink.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, that's tasty.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILES
{DIALOGUE}: 100% Pinot Noir.
{DIALOGUE}: Single vineyard.
{DIALOGUE}: They don't even make it anymore.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: Pinot Noir?
{DIALOGUE}: How come it's white?
{DIALOGUE}: Doesn't noir mean dark?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILES
{DIALOGUE}: Jesus.
{DIALOGUE}: Don't ask questions like that up in the wine country.
{DIALOGUE}: They'll think you're a moron.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: Just tell me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILES
{DIALOGUE}: Color in the red wines comes from the skins.
{DIALOGUE}: This juice is free run, so there's no skin contact in the fermentation, ergo no color.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{META_DATA}: (not really listening)
{DIALOGUE}: Sure is tasty.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. FREEWAY - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Saab heads north.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. SAAB - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The boys continue to drink and drive.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILES
{DIALOGUE}: Did you read the latest draft, by the way?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, yeah.
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILES
{DIALOGUE}: And?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: I liked it a lot.
{DIALOGUE}: A lot of improvements.
{DIALOGUE}: It just seemed overall, I don't know, tighter, more... congealed or something.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILES
{DIALOGUE}: How about the new ending?
{DIALOGUE}: Did you like that?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: Oh yeah.
{DIALOGUE}: Much better.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILES
{DIALOGUE}: There is no new ending.
{DIALOGUE}: Page 750 on is exactly the same.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: Well, then I guess it must have felt new because everything leading up to it was so different.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. GAS STATION #1 - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Miles is pumping gas.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jack is stretching his legs nearby or perhaps cleaning the windshield.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A CELLPHONE RINGS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jack reaches into his pocket.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{META_DATA}: (looking at the phone)
{DIALOGUE}: It's Christine.
{META_DATA}: (snapping it open)
{DIALOGUE}: Hey you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRISTINE (ON PHONE)
{DIALOGUE}: You guys having fun?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Christine's voice is so loud that Jack has to hold the phone away from his ear.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah.
{DIALOGUE}: All twenty minutes so far have been a blast.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRISTINE (ON THE PHONE)
{DIALOGUE}: Good.
{DIALOGUE}: That's good.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A silence, then --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: So what's up?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRISTINE (ON THE PHONE)
{DIALOGUE}: Just seeing how you're doing.
{DIALOGUE}: And, um, Mom and I were starting to look over the seating charts again, and we're wondering if you wanted Tony Levin to sit next to the Feldmans, or should he be at one of the singles tables?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jack looks at Miles in a mute appeal for sympathy.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRISTINE (ON THE PHONE)
{DIALOGUE}: So what do you think?
{DIALOGUE}: With the Feldmans?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jack hasn't even really heard the question.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah.
{DIALOGUE}: The Feldmans.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the conversation continues, Miles replaces the GAS PUMP, screws the GAS CAP back on, and together the guys get back into the car.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We DRIVE AWAY WITH THEM.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRISTINE (ON THE PHONE)
{DIALOGUE}: Really?
{DIALOGUE}: Because I don't know, I was thinking that --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: Well, then put him at the singles table.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRISTINE (ON THE PHONE)
{DIALOGUE}: The problem with that is that then there's one extra --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: Then put him with the Feldmans.
{DIALOGUE}: Whatever you and your Mom decide is fine with me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRISTINE (ON THE PHONE)
{DIALOGUE}: Don't dismiss me.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm trying to include you in this decision.
{DIALOGUE}: He's your friend.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: I didn't dismiss you.
{DIALOGUE}: I told you what I thought, but it didn't seem to matter, so you decide.
{DIALOGUE}: Besides, this is supposed to be my time with Miles.
{DIALOGUE}: I hope you're not going to call every five minutes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRISTINE (ON THE PHONE)
{DIALOGUE}: I'm not going to call every five minutes, but this is important.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: Honey, I'm just saying you know I need a little space before the wedding.
{DIALOGUE}: Isn't that the point of this?
{DIALOGUE}: Isn't that what we talked about with Dr. Gertler?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A silence.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Then --
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRISTINE (ON THE PHONE)
{DIALOGUE}: Why are you being so defensive?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: I don't know, Christine.
{DIALOGUE}: Perhaps it's because I feel attacked.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRISTINE (ON THE PHONE)
{DIALOGUE}: I ask you one simple question, and suddenly I'm attacking you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: Listen.
{DIALOGUE}: I'll call you when we get there, and we can talk about it then, okay?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRISTINE (ON THE PHONE)
{DIALOGUE}: Bye.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JACK
{DIALOGUE}: I love you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRISTINE (ON THE PHONE)
{DIALOGUE}: Bye.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jack SLAMS his cellphone shut, momentarily blinded with rage.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MILES
{DIALOGUE}: Tony Levin?
{DIALOGUE}: Why did you fucking invite Tony Levin?
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. 405 FREEWAY - LATE AFTERNOON
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Saab heads north -- now passing through LOS ANGELES.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT./EXT. SAAB - LATE AFTERNOON
